1:# Recipe 12.6: Python Implementation Example
11:## Setup
50:## Configuration and Constants
68:# Structured logging. In production, ship JSON-formatted records
69:# to CloudWatch Logs Insights for cross-call investigation.
70:# Revenue-cycle records are PHI by association; log structural
71:# metadata only (run_id, payer_id, claim_count, total_amount_band,
72:# runtime_ms), never raw claim numbers, never patient identifiers,
73:# never service dates tied to identifiable encounters, never the
74:# per-claim denial-reason text.
78:# Adaptive retry handles throttling from S3, DynamoDB, EventBridge,
79:# CloudWatch, and SageMaker. The weekly cash-flow pipeline is a
80:# scheduled batch job that touches every open claim, so retries
81:# should be quick and capped. A stuck dependency must not balloon
82:# a 30-minute weekly window into a multi-hour incident that blocks
83:# the Monday morning treasury review.
87:# Module-level clients. Reused across function calls within the
88:# pipeline so each call does not pay the connection cost. The
89:# demo wires up MockS3 / MockTable / MockEventBus / MockCloudWatch
90:# via run_demo() and never touches these real handles; they are
91:# staged here so production wiring is a one-line swap. boto3
92:# client and resource construction is lazy (no network call until
93:# first use), so the unused handles are free at import. The
94:# `sagemaker` client is the control-plane handle (CreateTrainingJob,
95:# DescribeTrainingJob, model registry) that Gap to Production
96:# describes; the `lambda_client` is staged for a future
97:# orchestration helper that invokes the per-claim Monte Carlo
98:# Lambda outside the Step Functions state machine.
119:# --- Resource Names ---
120:# Fill these in with your actual resource names. The demo prints
121:# what it would write rather than failing if the resources do
122:# not exist; see run_demo() at the bottom.
134:# --- Versioning ---
135:# Every weekly forecast carries the model version and the contract
136:# library version active at the time of generation. This is how
137:# a future audit reconstructs which curves and which contract
138:# assumptions produced which forecast on which week.
142:# --- Forecast Parameters ---
143:# 13-week (one quarter) horizon is the default for cash-flow
144:# forecasts because that is the standard treasury-planning window.
145:# 26-week and 52-week variants are reasonable extensions; the
146:# longer the horizon, the more the patient-responsibility tail
147:# dominates the uncertainty.
152:# --- Payer Catalog ---
153:# Per-payer configuration covering the small panel the demo
154:# operates on. Production maintains a curated table with hundreds
155:# of entries managed by the institutional revenue-cycle team.
156:# Each entry carries: the canonical payer identifier, the payer
157:# class (medicare / medicaid / commercial / self_pay / wc_auto),
158:# the typical first-pass denial rate, the appeal recovery rate
159:# (probability that a denied claim is recovered through appeal),
160:# the appeal lag in days, the contract effective date (curves
161:# train only on data after this), and the display name for
162:# surfaced payloads.
211:# --- Seasonality and Calendar ---
212:# Multiplicative seasonality factors applied at the per-week
213:# aggregation step. Production fits these from data using an
214:# STL or X-13ARIMA-SEATS decomposition; the demo uses fixed
215:# illustrative factors that capture the typical "Medicare and
216:# Medicaid pay slower in late December and early January due
217:# to year-end claim re-routing" pattern.
224:# --- AR Aging Buckets ---
225:# Standard healthcare AR aging buckets for surfaced reporting.
226:# The forecast surfaces aging-bucket-conditional probabilities
227:# so the finance team sees not just total expected cash but
228:# how much of it comes from "fresh" AR vs. "old" AR.
237:# --- Synthetic Data ---
238:# Knobs for the demo's synthetic-history generator. The ranges
239:# produce a small but realistic-shaped two-year history with
240:# five payers so you can see the pipeline fit per-payer curves
241:# and forecast cash by week.
246:# Deploy-time guardrail. Any blank resource name is a deploy-time
247:# bug, not a runtime surprise.
